questionTemplates.text:
W: The piano sounds terrible.
M: I wish I could ask for my money back. This performance is really a bad one.
{a}

M: Tomorrow I'll bring you some books. Is there anything special you'd like to eat?
W: I don't feel like reading or eating, but buy me a hair brush on your way here.
{a}

M: Has Professor Arnold from Sydney University arrived?
W: I'll have to check. Then I'll get back to you straightway.
{a}

M: Let's go for a nice walk into the country this afternoon.
W: I certainly could enjoy the exercise, but I've agreed to go with Alice to buy some clothes.
{a}

M: How would you like your coffee?
W: Milky one without sugar, please.
{a}

W: Bring an umbrella with you to the baseball game! The weather report on the radio said it was going to rain today.
M: I'm not going to bring an umbrella. It's beautiful outside! There aren't any clouds in the sky. I don't want to carry anything.
{a}

M: What kind of music do you like?
W: I like pop music and rock music. But, rock music is my favorite.
{a}

F: Have you found your youngest brother, Tom?
M: Yes. He was picked up by a policeman.
{a}

M: How about your hotel?
F: Not very good, I'm afraid.
{a}

W: Lots of people enjoy dancing, do you?
M: Believe it or not, that is the last thing I want to do.
{a}

M: Hello, Anne. This is Larry at the office. Is Fred at home?
W: No, Larry. He's in class now. He'll be home for lunch, though.
{a}

F: Jack, would you like to go to cinema with me?
M: I'm tired. I'd like to watch TV at home.
{a}

W: Good morning, can I help you?
M: Yes, I'd like to send this letter by airmail.
{a}

M: Hello, Susan. Could I speak to Jim, please?
F: I'm afraid he is not here now.
{a}

W: It's eight o'clock now. You are half an hour late.
M: Sorry, I'll be on time next time.
{a}

W: Mr. Johnson, have you heard the morning news report? Mill has resigned his post as Prime Minister.
M: I didn't turn on the radio this morning, but I did see the headlines. If you remember, he threatened to leave the office at the last cabinet meeting.
{a}

F: After this film is over, I'm going to Mary's.
M: I'm tired. I'm going home.
{a}

W: Listen!  Someone is knocking at the door, Jim?
M: It must be Kate.
{a}

M: Bob is supposed to arrive by 8:00.
W: His wife said he had left home at 7:50, so he won't be here before 8:30.
{a}

M: It's nearly seven o'clock. Let's go.
F: No hurry. The party starts at seven thirty.
{a}

M: Mrs. Winter, I need your advice, I want to buy a dress for my wife, can you tell me where I can get one at a reasonable price?
W: Sure, go to Richard's. It has the latest styles and gives a 30% discount to husbands who shop alone.
{a}

W: Have you found anything wrong with my heart?
M: Not yet. I'm still examining. I'll let you know the result tomorrow.
{a}

F: Can I help you, sir? These hats are almost sold out.
M: Do they? Then, I'd like to try on one.
{a}

F: Joh, this is my sister Jeany.
M: How do you do!
{a}

W: It's freezing cold. Let me make some coffee to warm us up. Do you want a piece of pie as well?
M: Coffee sounds great. But I'm going to have dinner with some friends in a while, so I'd better skip the pie.
{a}

M: I'm going to drop my Information Science class. It means too early in the morning.
W: Is that really the good reason to drop the class, Tony?
{a}

W: Did you turn off the lights and check the locks on all the doors?
M: Yes, I told the Johnsons that we'd be gone for two weeks. They promise to keep an eye on the house for us.
{a}

W: Can I help you?
M: Yes, I bought these shoes here two days ago. But they some too small and press against my feet.
{a}
